,"1510":"1510","1585":"1585","4 April 1592":"4 April 1592","23 May 1631":"23 May 1631","1549":"1549","1548":"1548","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Carleton, Craven, North Yorkshire, England":"Carleton, North Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Wray, Lancashire, England":"Wray, Lancashire, England","Leeds, St Peter, Yorkshire, England":"Leeds Minster, Leeds, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Mirfield, Yorkshire, England":"Mirfield, Yorkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Watterhouse","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (mainly Yorkshire, Lancashire, and Midlands): topographic name for someone who lived in a house by a stretch of water, from Middle English <i>water</i> ‘water’ + <i>hous</i> ‘house’.","History: Richard Waterhouse, a tanner from Yorkshire, England, emigrated to Portsmouth, NH, in 1669."],"variants":[{"name":"Watrous","meanings":["English: variant of   Waterhouse  . This surname is now rare in Britain."]}]},{"name":"Ann","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Anne .  In the U.S. <i>Ann</i> is the more frequent spelling."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":26,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705202,"age":35,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705205,"age":46,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705207,"age":62,"year":"1585","julianDay":2299970,"title":"The First English Colony is Established in America","description":"England established its first colony in North America in 1585 as a way to generate additional wealth. The colony was named Virginia, after the virgin Queen Elizabeth I.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705208,"age":64,"year":"1587","julianDay":2300700,"title":"Elizabeth I Signs Death Warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots","description":"Elizabeth I signed the death warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots, on February 1, 1587, as she was found guilty of plotting to assasinate Elizabeth. Mary, Queen of Scots, was beheaded at Fotheringhay Castle in England on February 8, 1587.","url":"https://www.elizabethi.org/mary_queen_of_scots/","urlTitle":"Elizabeth I.org - Mary Queen of Scots","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705212,"age":97,"year":"1620","julianDay":2312753,"title":"The Pilgrims Board the Mayflower","description":"\"The Pilgrims boarded the Mayflower in search of religious freedom in the New World in September 1620. The Mayflower set sail from Plymouth, England, with 102 passengers, 40 of whom called themselves \"\"Saints.\"\" After two stormy months at sea, the ship reached the New World. Nearly half of the group died during their first winter due to malnutrition and the harsh New England winter.\"","url":"https://www.themayflowersociety.org/the-pilgrims/pilgrim-history","urlTitle":"The Mayflower Society - Pilgrim History","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Ann Watterhouse was born in 1523, in Yorkshire, England, her father, Gregory Watterhouse, was 13 and her mother, Ann, was 13. She married Richard Wilcock in 1545, in Mirfield, Yorkshire, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. She died in 1631, in Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 108, and was buried in Leeds Minster, Leeds, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1523–1631":"1523–1631","1525–1583":"1525–1583","1545–1592":"1545–1592","1548–Female":"1548–Surnud","1560–1623":"1560–1623","1510–Male":"1510–Surnud","1510–Female":"1510–Surnud","1583":"1583","1560":"1560","1592":"1592","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1525":"1525","1623":"1623","1523":"1523","1545":"1545","1631":"1631","1620":"1620","1587":"1587","1510":"1510","1585":"1585","4 April 1592":"4. aprill 1592","23 May 1631":"23. mai 1631","1549":"1549","1548":"1548","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Carleton, Craven, North Yorkshire, England":"Carleton, North Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Wray, Lancashire, England":"Wray, Lancashire, England","Leeds, St Peter, Yorkshire, England":"Leeds Minster, Leeds, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Mirfield, Yorkshire, England":"Mirfield, Yorkshire, England"},"fi":{"1523–1631":"1523–1631","1525–1583":"1525–1583","1545–1592":"1545–1592","1548–Female":"1548–Kuollut","1560–1623":"1560–1623","1510–Male":"1510–Kuollut","1510–Female":"1510–Kuollut","1583":"1583","1560":"1560","1592":"1592","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1525":"1525","1623":"1623","1523":"1523","1545":"1545","1631":"1631","1620":"1620","1587":"1587","1510":"1510","1585":"1585","4 April 1592":"4. huhtikuuta 1592","23 May 1631":"23. toukokuuta 1631","1549":"1549","1548":"1548","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Carleton, Craven, North Yorkshire, England":"Carleton, North Yorkshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Yorksh